sent_0: The Ukraine government reportedly sent protesters in Kiev a creepy text message.
sent_1: This is how they could have done it.
sent_10: There are a few different ways the Ukrainian government could have done it, according to Ashkan Soltani, an independent privacy researcher.
sent_11: The easiest would have been for the government to ask Ukrainian cellphone providers to give them a list of numbers that were connected to a certain cellphone tower, or a few towers, in a certain interval of time.
sent_12: This is what is commonly referred to as " tower dumps ."
sent_13: This would imply the collaboration of the cellphone companies, but all the major Ukrainian providers on Tuesday denied they had anything to do with this incident.
sent_14: "We declare our innocence," wrote MTS on its Facebook page according to a translation of the statement.
sent_15: "It was carried out by using equipment that does not belong to MTS."
sent_16: Another provider, Kyivstar, penned a similar denial.
sent_17: "Attackers are using illegal equipment for such mailings.
sent_18: We know of the existence of equipment (the so-called 'pirate base stations') that allows you to send SMS and make calls to mobile phones subscribers to any operators that are in a certain area," the company wrote on Facebook.
sent_19: Here's the catch: The equipment to which they refer actually exists, and with it authorities wouldn't need the providers' help to identify whoever was in downtown Kiev near the protests and send them the text messages.
sent_2: As mass riots continued on the streets of Kiev, protesters, as well as other people in the area, received a mysterious text message on Monday evening.
sent_20: The easiest way would be to use a so-called "IMSI catcher," which is a portable device built to act as a cell tower and trick nearby cellphones into connecting to it, Soltani explained to Mashable .
sent_21: "They're essentially fake base stations," Soltani told Mashable .
sent_22: Once a cellphone is connected to one of these International Mobile Subscriber Number (IMSI) catchers, the device captures a deluge of information, including identifying details such as the IMSI and the Electronic Serial Number (ESM).
sent_23: Once the IMSI catcher is connected to a series of cellphones, it can broadcast text messages like the one the protesters received.
sent_24: Devices like these are normally employed by police departments to track suspected criminals, but their use has stirred controversy because they don't discriminate.
sent_25: Any cellphone in their range gets caught in their surveillance net, and these devices are also designed to intercept phone calls and messages.
sent_26: There are a lot of commercial IMSI catchers , costing anywhere from $20,000 to around $140,000, depending on their features and range.
sent_27: They are sometimes referred to as "Stingrays," from the most widely known of this devices, made by Harris Corporation .
sent_28: But hackers have been able to build similar machines with just $1,500.
sent_29: According to Costin Raiu, a security researcher at Kaspersky Lab, this is the most likely theory, assuming the cellphone providers did not cooperate.
sent_3: "Dear subscriber, you are registered as a participant in a mass disturbance," the message read, as first reported by The New York Times .
sent_30: While it's still unclear who sent these messages in Kiev, it's clear why they did it.
sent_31: "You can scare people into thinking that they have been targeted much more narrowly by writing a message that implies essentially 'we caught you personally rioting,'" said Galperin.
sent_32: The protesters, however, were not scared away, as clashes continued after the message was broadcast.
sent_4: The text came from a number only identified as 111, but the Times suggests Ukrainian authorities were behind it.
sent_5: The country's Interior Ministry, however, denied sending the messages, as later reported by The Guardian .
sent_6: But regardless of who was responsible for the SMS messages, how did they do it?
sent_7: How did they pinpoint only certain cellphones in a specific area?
sent_8: It turns out, something like this wouldn't be that hard to carry out.
sent_9: "It is very easy to send messages out to everybody who was in one particular area, at one particular time," said Eva Galperin, an activist at the Electronic Frontier Foundation and an expert in surveillance technology.
title: Someone Sent a Mysterious Mass Text to Protesters in Kiev

sent_0: Ukraine's parliament has passed legislation that would allow the government to impose sanctions on Russia.
sent_1: The bill was approved in a final reading on August 14.
sent_10: The law simply establishes the legal right to implement them," the statement said.
sent_11: A version of the bill passed on first reading on August 12 had included provisions allowing the censoring of media deemed a national security threat.
sent_12: Those provisions were removed from the final version of the bill, however.
sent_13: Rights groups had said the law would give the council "draconian" powers to restrict media and could return a nation once celebrated for media freedoms to Soviet-era levels of censorship.
sent_14: In a statement, the representative on media freedom for the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), Dunja Mijatovic, welcomed the move to drop the media provisions as a "step in the right direction."
sent_15: "The provisions could potentially endanger free media and pluralism in Ukraine," she said, "and by dropping them the legislators have taken a decision to protect and ensure free media and freedom of expression, rather than restricting free speech."
sent_16: Also on August 14, Ukraine's parliament approved a bill to allow gas-transit facilities to be leased on a joint-venture basis with participation from EU and U.S. firms.
sent_17: The measure says Ukraine will hold 51 percent and foreign partners will be offered 49 percent in the venture.
sent_18: It covers both transit pipelines and underground gas-storage facilities.
sent_19: The law passed by 228 votes -- two more than the minimum necessary.
sent_2: It provides for sanctions against 172 individuals and 65 entities in Russia and other countries for supporting and financing "terrorism" in Ukraine, though actual sanctions would need approval from Ukraine's National Security and Defense Council.
sent_20: Ukraine is making efforts to become less dependent on Russian gas after suffering three cutoffs of natural-gas supplies from Russia in less than nine years.
sent_21: At the same time, Kyiv wants to provide more reliable transit for Russian gas to the EU market.
sent_22: Kyiv says the measure will bring in investment and remove the need for the South Stream pipeline, which Russia is building to take gas to southeastern Europe across the Black Sea, bypassing Ukraine.
sent_3: A total of 244 lawmakers in the Verkhovna Rada supported the sanctions.
sent_4: Prime Minister Arseniy Yatsenyuk told parliament after the August 14 vote that Ukraine had taken a historic step.
sent_5: "By approving the law on sanctions, we showed that the country is able to protect itself," he said.
sent_6: "The law should give a clear answer to any aggressor or terrorist who threatens our national security, our government, and our citizens."
sent_7: The names of those Russian individuals and companies targeted by the sanctions will not be published until President Petro Poroshenko has signed the law into force.
sent_8: Naftohaz, Ukraine's state-run energy firm, said in a statement on August 13 that future sanctions against Russia would not necessarily target Russia's gas giant Gazprom, however.
sent_9: "The adoption of the sanctions law will not lead automatically to sanctions against any entity, including Gazprom.
title: Ukraine Passes Law On Russia Sanctions, Gas Pipelines

sent_0: Public opinion poll was conducted by the Ilko  Kucheriv Democratic Initiatives Foundation together with Kyiv International Institute of Sociology  in the period between February, 8-18 2014.
sent_1: 2032 respondents were interviewed  in all the districts  of Ukraine (including  Kyiv) and in Crimea according to the random sample, which was representative for  all the population of Ukraine older than 18 years.
sent_10: The main part of  supporters of this idea of unification with Russia is in the East (26%) and South (19%), while the smallest part is in the Center (5%) and West (1%) of Ukraine.
sent_11: By regions  majority of integration with Russia in one state  is in Crimea  (41%), Donetsk district (33%), Lugansk district (24%), Odessa district (24%), Zaporizhzhya (17%) and Kharkiv  (15%) districts, but even there  support  to the current status of relations  with Russia   - as two independent and  friendly  states – prevails.
sent_12: Among Russians  desire to have Ukraine and Russia as two independent and friendly states (with open borders, without visas and customs houses) prevails as well as among Ukrainians (68% and 63% respectively).
sent_13: Integration into one state is supported  by 9% of Ukrainians and 32% of Russians.
sent_14: There is direct dependence  between  desire to unite with Russia into  a single state and age of respondents:  among youth   up to 30 years old  5% want this unification to be realized, among people of 30-54 years old – 11% support that, and  among people older than 55 years – 17%.
sent_15: It is obvious, that among supporters of joining the Custom Union, there is more people supporting unification  with Russia  (26,5%), than among  those, oriented on joining the EU (1%).
sent_16: However,  even among supporters of entering the Custom Union  majority   wants  to preserve the status-quo in relations with Russia (69%).
sent_17: Among  people, having negative attitude towards Maidan,  only 21% wants to unite with Russia into a single state.
sent_18: Among supporters of political parties  the highest percentage  of people, who wants join Ukraine to join Russia, is among  communists’ electorate  (35,5%), but even in this case majority  consider that Ukraine and Russia should be friendly independent states (63%).
sent_19: Among  Party of Regions  voters 28% support unification with Russia.
sent_2: Statistical error doesn’t  exceed  2,2% (without design -effect).
sent_20: In Russia  16% of population support  unification with Ukraine into one state.
sent_3: Question included by  the Ilko Kucheriv Democratic Initiatives Foundation were financed  in the framework of the project “Public sociological consortium” by the European union, MATRA programme  of the Kingdom of Netherlands, International Renaissance Foundation, and also  in the framework of the project  “Stimulating dialog on transition processes” by the National Endowment for Democracy (USA).
sent_4: Data from public opinion poll, conducted by Russian research organization Levada Centre  is provided for comparison.
sent_5: Levada Centre  conducted  representative for Russia public opinion poll  on February,  21-25 2014 and interviewed  1603 respondents older than 18 years in 130 settlements in 45 districts of the country.
sent_6: Statistical error doesn’t exceed 3,4%.
sent_7: Ukrainians don’t want visas and borders with Russia, but at the same time don’t want  to be united with Russia  in a single state   In Ukraine, as well as in Russia  majority of respondents  wants both countries to be independent, but friendly  - with open borders, without visas and customs houses (in Ukraine – 68%, in Russia – 59%).
sent_8: In Ukraine  with numbers  have decreased  since November, 2013 by 5%, in Russia – increased  by 4%.
sent_9: Integration with  Russia into a single state   is supported by 12% of respondents in Ukraine, and  during recent years  this number has decreased from 20% to 9%,  but after Maidan – increased by 3%.
title: HOW RELATIONS BETWEEN UKRAINE AND RUSSIA SHOULD LOOK LIKE? PUBLIC OPINION POLL RESULTS

sent_0: VORONEZH — The son of Cuban revolutionary Fidel Castro declared that the island nation recognizes Crimea as a part of Russia and urged the Kremlin to follow Havana's example and stand firm in the face of international sanctions.
sent_1: Fidel Castro Diaz-Balart, scientific adviser of the State Council of the Republic of Cuba and vice president of the Academy of Sciences of Cuba, made the remarks while accepting an honorary doctorate from his former university in Voronezh over the weekend.
sent_10: Castro Diaz-Balart scoffed at the steps that the U.S. and European Union have taken to isolate Russia, including the suspension of its membership in the Group of Eight and the placement of travel bans and asset freezes on people close to Putin.
sent_11: "Cuba has extensive experience of living in isolation from the U.S.," Castro Diaz-Balart said.
sent_12: The Voronezh visit was something of a homecoming for Castro Diaz-Balart, the eldest son of Castro from his first wife.
sent_13: He enrolled at the university as a physical education student in 1968 and changed his major to nuclear physics two years later, acting under the influence of the university's nuclear physicists.
sent_14: He went on to graduate with honors from Moscow State University.
sent_15: Castro Diaz-Balart then worked at the Joint Institute of Nuclear Research in Dubna before earning his first doctorate in 1978.
sent_16: In 1999, he received a second doctorate, this time from the Kurchatov Institute of Nuclear Energy, and he also holds honorary doctorates from Moscow State University and Rostov State University.
sent_17: On Saturday, the Voronezh university gave Diaz-Balart his third honorary doctorate from Russia and an award titled "For Merit to Voronezh State University" at a ceremony attended by Voronezh Governor Alexei Gordeyev.
sent_18: After referring to Crimea and the uprising in Ukraine, Diaz-Balart finished his speech with a quote from his father: "When all great revolutions come to an end, there will only be one left — the great revolution of science and knowledge.
sent_19: And it will never finish."
sent_2: While Russia is under enormous international pressure for annexing Crimea from Ukraine last month, Castro Diaz-Balart reaffirmed that Cuba officially recognized the referendum results in Crimea that paved the way for President Vladimir Putin to sign the annexation agreement.
sent_3: He also noted that Cuba joined 10 other countries in refusing to condemn the annexation during a vote of the United Nations General Assembly on Thursday.
sent_4: One hundred countries approved the resolution, while 58 countries abstained.
sent_5: "During the UN vote, Cuba proved that it remains a friend of Russia and of other countries of the former Soviet Union forever," Castro Diaz-Balart said in the speech Saturday at Voronezh State University.
sent_6: He insisted that Cuba was also a friend of Ukraine.
sent_7: "The people of Ukraine, as I understand it, do not have any claims against the Russians," he said, following the Kremlin line.
sent_8: "It is those in power who are acting in their own self-interest."
sent_9: Fidel Castro Díaz-Balart attending a ceremony where he received an honorary doctorate at Voronezh State University on Saturday.
title: Visiting Russia, Fidel Castro's Son Scoffs at U.S. Sanctions Over Crimea

sent_0: Experts say there's motivation beyond altruism for the US and EU trying to forge closer ties with the country in crisis
sent_1: As the crisis in Ukraine  drags on into its fourth month, the geopolitics of the situation have grown increasingly complex, with more diplomats, leaders and interested parties opining on each and every development in the country.
sent_10: Ukraine is also one of the world’s largest growers of corn and wheat, and exports it to EU countries and elsewhere.
sent_11: Analysts believe that with heavy investment, Ukraine’s agricultural sector could grow exponentially.
sent_12: Beyond maintaining the current flow of trade, if Ukraine shuns Russia, experts believe EU countries will be able to benefit from increased trade with Ukraine.
sent_13: That’s why EU officials are attempting to sign a  free-trade agreement with Ukraine  even as the crisis escalates.
sent_14: And some say the country may even be able to eventually join the European Union.
sent_15: But more important than crops and cars — for Ukraine, the EU and U.S. — is gas.
sent_16: Experts say the EU and U.S. could profit economically if Ukraine begins to rely less on Gazprom, Russia’s quasi-governmental oil and gas giant.
sent_17: They point out that the protests in Ukraine started partially because of Ukraine’s  near-complete reliance on Russian gas.
sent_18: And Ukraine has been trying to break away from that dependence for years.
sent_19: In November, it signed a $10 billion deal with Chevron to produce natural gas within Ukraine, but it could also look elsewhere for its supplies.
sent_2: President Barack Obama and leaders from the European Union, for example, have spoken at length on what they want for Ukraine — that it determine its own destiny, and not just any destiny, but one that is different from its past of playing economic lapdog to Russia.
sent_20: As the EU and U.S. discover new ways to extract oil and gas on their own soil — namely through hydraulic fracturing — and build liquefied natural-gas terminals to send it around the world, Ukraine could become a viable market.
sent_21: “The whole natural gas market is changing dramatically,” USIP’s Taylor said.
sent_22: “Over the next five years, there’s going to be dramatic changes in the flows of gas, and the leverage Russians have over the EU and Ukraine is going to decline.”
sent_23: Because Europe also relies heavily on Gazprom, disrupting Ukraine’s relations with Russia is a risky prospect.
sent_24: Some believe it’s no coincidence that the countries that rely most on Russia for gas, especially Germany,  have been more reluctant  than the U.S. to suggest sanctions against Russia.
sent_25: The EU may be seeking a middle ground — making sure the gas can keep flowing while Ukraine also builds closer ties with European countries.
sent_26: At least for the U.S., isolating Gazprom might not be as controversial of an option.
sent_27: In the midst of a hydraulic fracturing-created gas boom, the U.S. has been looking to increase gas exports dramatically over the next few years.
sent_28: So the possibility that Ukraine, and therefore the EU, might break away from Russia’s gas supply might be considered both a geopolitical win and cash bonanza by U.S. politicians.
sent_29: “The United States has abundant supplies of natural gas — an energy source that is in demand by many of our allies — and the U.S. Department of Energy’s excruciatingly slow approval process amounts to a de facto ban on American natural gas exports that Vladimir Putin has happily exploited to finance his geopolitical goals,” House Speaker John Boehner said Tuesday.
sent_3: Going beyond the platitudes of supporting Ukraine's autonomy, however, what has gone without much discussion is why the cash-strapped European Union and the U.S. were motivated to step into the fray — to potentially spend billions of dollars on a country that without the support of Russia might face economic collapse.
sent_30: “We should not force our allies to remain dependent on Putin for their energy needs.
sent_31: Ending this de facto ban and expediting approval of natural gas exports is one clear step the U.S. can take to stand by our allies and stand up to Russian aggression, while creating American jobs at the same time.”
sent_32: Some analysts say breaking EU and Ukrainian reliance on Russia’s gas might not only be about the economy, but about something the U.S. has  wanted to do ever since the Cold War : prove it, and not Russia, is the world’s preeminent superpower.
sent_33: “The U.S. has never gotten over the Cold War, and (U.S.) leaders view Russia as a potential adversary,” said Michael Klare, a professor of peace and world security studies at Hampshire College.
sent_34: “ (Russia is) a petro-state.
sent_35: Take that away and Putin’s power disappears.”
sent_4: With tension from military posturing in Crimea increasing, and the potential for bloodshed potent, foreign policy watchers say it’s important to suss out soon why exactly the EU and U.S. — which have been focused inwardly on domestic issues since the global financial crisis — now seem so intent on helping determine the direction of Ukraine.
sent_5: Besides pure altruism, they say the countries have a lot to lose if Ukraine falls further into crisis, and perhaps just as much to gain if it doesn’t.
sent_6: “This is a big country in the center of Europe that can affect the stability of all of Europe,” said William Taylor, vice president at the  U.S. Institute for Peace.
sent_7: “A civil war there would affect energy supplies, trade, everything.”
sent_8: Taylor and others believe all of the West, especially the EU, have a vested economic interested in making sure Ukraine stays stable.
sent_9: For one, the EU exports over $20 billion in goods — primarily machinery, vehicles and industrial chemicals — to  Ukraine annually .
title: What does the West want from Ukraine?

sent_0: Major nationalist role in protests worries many in Ukraine and abroad
sent_1: As Ukraine’s opposition movement vows to continue its “revolution” with more protests and a general strike, an ultra- nationalist party is playing a leading role and former symbols of the far-right fringe are moving into the political mainstream.
sent_10: Today’s “enemies” are president Viktor Yanukovich , whom critics accuse of leading Ukraine away from the European Union and back into Russia’s embrace.
sent_11: Svoboda’s activists are now playing a major role in running Kiev’s main protest camp and buildings occupied by demonstrators.
sent_12: They were also prominent in resisting riot police who tried to storm the camp and in the highly symbolic toppling of a statue of Vladimir Lenin.
sent_13: Svoboda’s leader, former surgeon Oleh Tyahnybok, rouses protesters with firebrand rhetoric attacking the “anti-Ukrainian” forces running the country, and he has met visiting senior EU and US diplomats who would have shunned him in other circumstances.
sent_14: Tyahnybok’s diatribes against corrupt politicians, tycoons and the Kremlin play well with the crowd, and the protests are helping him to push Svoboda towards Ukraine’s political centre.
sent_15: How Svoboda will emerge from Ukraine’s turmoil remains to be seen, but its growing influence, hostility towards Russia and praise for Bandera could deepen the country’s divisions.
sent_16: Svoboda also presents an easy target to the protesters’ foes: Ukraine’s premier Mykola Azarov has called them “Nazis and extremists”, while Russian president Vladimir Putin compared the rallies to a “pogrom”.
sent_2: Flying above crowds in Kiev and other cities, the flags of Ukraine and the European Union mingle with red-and-black “blood and soil” nationalist banners.
sent_3: Across the country, the rallying cry of this revolt booms out countless times every day: “Glory to Ukraine! Glory to the heroes!”
sent_4: The flag and the mantra of the protests were first used by guerrillas in the 1940s, who fought against Nazi and Soviet occupiers in a bid to carve out an independent Ukraine.
sent_5: They are still lionised by many people in western regions, while people in southern and eastern Ukraine, with closer ties to Russia , deride them as Nazi collaborators.
sent_6: Historians say the guerrillas sometimes fought alongside Adolf Hitler’s forces in the hope of securing support for a sovereign Ukraine, and were involved in the killing of tens of thousands of Poles and the German-led mass murder and deportation of Jews.
sent_7: On New Year’s Day, about 15,000 people took part in a torchlit procession through Kiev to mark 105 years since the birth of wartime nationalist leader Stepan Bandera, who is honoured with statues in western Ukraine but reviled in regions closer to Russia, as well as by Jews and Poles.
sent_8: “Glory to the nation, death to the enemies!” chanted the crowd, led by members of a nationalist party called Svoboda (“Freedom”), which has risen rapidly from relative obscurity to be the fourth-largest party in parliament and jointly runs councils in western Ukraine.
sent_9: Liberal opposition parties distanced themselves from the march.
title: Ukraine right revives wartime symbols amid 'revolution'

sent_0: The Ukraine government reportedly sent protesters in Kiev a creepy text message.
sent_1: This is how they could have done it.
sent_10: There are a few different ways the Ukrainian government could have done it, according to Ashkan Soltani, an independent privacy researcher.
sent_11: The easiest would have been for the government to ask Ukrainian cellphone providers to give them a list of numbers that were connected to a certain cellphone tower, or a few towers, in a certain interval of time.
sent_12: This is what is commonly referred to as " tower dumps ."
sent_13: This would imply the collaboration of the cellphone companies, but all the major Ukrainian providers on Tuesday denied they had anything to do with this incident.
sent_14: "We declare our innocence," wrote MTS on its Facebook page according to a translation of the statement.
sent_15: "It was carried out by using equipment that does not belong to MTS."
sent_16: Another provider, Kyivstar, penned a similar denial.
sent_17: "Attackers are using illegal equipment for such mailings.
sent_18: We know of the existence of equipment (the so-called 'pirate base stations') that allows you to send SMS and make calls to mobile phones subscribers to any operators that are in a certain area," the company wrote on Facebook.
sent_19: Here's the catch: The equipment to which they refer actually exists, and with it authorities wouldn't need the providers' help to identify whoever was in downtown Kiev near the protests and send them the text messages.
sent_2: As mass riots continued on the streets of Kiev, protesters, as well as other people in the area, received a mysterious text message on Monday evening.
sent_20: The easiest way would be to use a so-called "IMSI catcher," which is a portable device built to act as a cell tower and trick nearby cellphones into connecting to it, Soltani explained to Mashable .
sent_21: "They're essentially fake base stations," Soltani told Mashable .
sent_22: Once a cellphone is connected to one of these International Mobile Subscriber Number (IMSI) catchers, the device captures a deluge of information, including identifying details such as the IMSI and the Electronic Serial Number (ESM).
sent_23: Once the IMSI catcher is connected to a series of cellphones, it can broadcast text messages like the one the protesters received.
sent_24: Devices like these are normally employed by police departments to track suspected criminals, but their use has stirred controversy because they don't discriminate.
sent_25: Any cellphone in their range gets caught in their surveillance net, and these devices are also designed to intercept phone calls and messages.
sent_26: There are a lot of commercial IMSI catchers , costing anywhere from $20,000 to around $140,000, depending on their features and range.
sent_27: They are sometimes referred to as "Stingrays," from the most widely known of this devices, made by Harris Corporation .
sent_28: But hackers have been able to build similar machines with just $1,500.
sent_29: According to Costin Raiu, a security researcher at Kaspersky Lab, this is the most likely theory, assuming the cellphone providers did not cooperate.
sent_3: "Dear subscriber, you are registered as a participant in a mass disturbance," the message read, as first reported by The New York Times .
sent_30: While it's still unclear who sent these messages in Kiev, it's clear why they did it.
sent_31: "You can scare people into thinking that they have been targeted much more narrowly by writing a message that implies essentially 'we caught you personally rioting,'" said Galperin.
sent_32: The protesters, however, were not scared away, as clashes continued after the message was broadcast.
sent_4: The text came from a number only identified as 111, but the Times suggests Ukrainian authorities were behind it.
sent_5: The country's Interior Ministry, however, denied sending the messages, as later reported by The Guardian .
sent_6: But regardless of who was responsible for the SMS messages, how did they do it?
sent_7: How did they pinpoint only certain cellphones in a specific area?
sent_8: It turns out, something like this wouldn't be that hard to carry out.
sent_9: "It is very easy to send messages out to everybody who was in one particular area, at one particular time," said Eva Galperin, an activist at the Electronic Frontier Foundation and an expert in surveillance technology.
title: Someone Sent a Mysterious Mass Text to Protesters in Kiev

sent_21: "They're essentially fake base stations," Soltani told Mashable .
sent_22: Once a cellphone is connected to one of these International Mobile Subscriber Number (IMSI) catchers, the device captures a deluge of information, including identifying details such as the IMSI and the Electronic Serial Number (ESM).
sent_23: Once the IMSI catcher is connected to a series of cellphones, it can broadcast text messages like the one the protesters received.
sent_24: Devices like these are normally employed by police departments to track suspected criminals, but their use has stirred controversy because they don't discriminate.
sent_25: Any cellphone in their range gets caught in their surveillance net, and these devices are also designed to intercept phone calls and messages.
sent_26: There are a lot of commercial IMSI catchers , costing anywhere from $20,000 to around $140,000, depending on their features and range.
sent_27: They are sometimes referred to as "Stingrays," from the most widely known of this devices, made by Harris Corporation .
sent_28: But hackers have been able to build similar machines with just $1,500.
sent_29: According to Costin Raiu, a security researcher at Kaspersky Lab, this is the most likely theory, assuming the cellphone providers did not cooperate.
sent_3: "Dear subscriber, you are registered as a participant in a mass disturbance," the message read, as first reported by The New York Times .
sent_30: While it's still unclear who sent these messages in Kiev, it's clear why they did it.
sent_31: "You can scare people into thinking that they have been targeted much more narrowly by writing a message that implies essentially 'we caught you personally rioting,'" said Galperin.
sent_32: The protesters, however, were not scared away, as clashes continued after the message was broadcast.
sent_4: The text came from a number only identified as 111, but the Times suggests Ukrainian authorities were behind it.
sent_5: The country's Interior Ministry, however, denied sending the messages, as later reported by The Guardian .
sent_6: But regardless of who was responsible for the SMS messages, how did they do it?
sent_7: How did they pinpoint only certain cellphones in a specific area?
sent_8: It turns out, something like this wouldn't be that hard to carry out.
sent_9: "It is very easy to send messages out to everybody who was in one particular area, at one particular time," said Eva Galperin, an activist at the Electronic Frontier Foundation and an expert in surveillance technology.
title: Someone Sent a Mysterious Mass Text to Protesters in Kiev

sent_0: Experts say there's motivation beyond altruism for the US and EU trying to forge closer ties with the country in crisis
sent_1: As the crisis in Ukraine  drags on into its fourth month, the geopolitics of the situation have grown increasingly complex, with more diplomats, leaders and interested parties opining on each and every development in the country.
sent_10: Ukraine is also one of the world’s largest growers of corn and wheat, and exports it to EU countries and elsewhere.
sent_11: Analysts believe that with heavy investment, Ukraine’s agricultural sector could grow exponentially.
sent_12: Beyond maintaining the current flow of trade, if Ukraine shuns Russia, experts believe EU countries will be able to benefit from increased trade with Ukraine.
sent_13: That’s why EU officials are attempting to sign a  free-trade agreement with Ukraine  even as the crisis escalates.
sent_14: And some say the country may even be able to eventually join the European Union.
sent_15: But more important than crops and cars — for Ukraine, the EU and U.S. — is gas.
sent_16: Experts say the EU and U.S. could profit economically if Ukraine begins to rely less on Gazprom, Russia’s quasi-governmental oil and gas giant.
sent_17: They point out that the protests in Ukraine started partially because of Ukraine’s  near-complete reliance on Russian gas.
sent_18: And Ukraine has been trying to break away from that dependence for years.
sent_19: In November, it signed a $10 billion deal with Chevron to produce natural gas within Ukraine, but it could also look elsewhere for its supplies.
sent_2: President Barack Obama and leaders from the European Union, for example, have spoken at length on what they want for Ukraine — that it determine its own destiny, and not just any destiny, but one that is different from its past of playing economic lapdog to Russia.
sent_20: As the EU and U.S. discover new ways to extract oil and gas on their own soil — namely through hydraulic fracturing — and build liquefied natural-gas terminals to send it around the world, Ukraine could become a viable market.
sent_21: “The whole natural gas market is changing dramatically,” USIP’s Taylor said.
sent_22: “Over the next five years, there’s going to be dramatic changes in the flows of gas, and the leverage Russians have over the EU and Ukraine is going to decline.”
sent_23: Because Europe also relies heavily on Gazprom, disrupting Ukraine’s relations with Russia is a risky prospect.
sent_24: Some believe it’s no coincidence that the countries that rely most on Russia for gas, especially Germany,  have been more reluctant  than the U.S. to suggest sanctions against Russia.
sent_25: The EU may be seeking a middle ground — making sure the gas can keep flowing while Ukraine also builds closer ties with European countries.
sent_26: At least for the U.S., isolating Gazprom might not be as controversial of an option.
sent_27: In the midst of a hydraulic fracturing-created gas boom, the U.S. has been looking to increase gas exports dramatically over the next few years.
sent_28: So the possibility that Ukraine, and therefore the EU, might break away from Russia’s gas supply might be considered both a geopolitical win and cash bonanza by U.S. politicians.
sent_29: “The United States has abundant supplies of natural gas — an energy source that is in demand by many of our allies — and the U.S. Department of Energy’s excruciatingly slow approval process amounts to a de facto ban on American natural gas exports that Vladimir Putin has happily exploited to finance his geopolitical goals,” House Speaker John Boehner said Tuesday.
sent_3: Going beyond the platitudes of supporting Ukraine's autonomy, however, what has gone without much discussion is why the cash-strapped European Union and the U.S. were motivated to step into the fray — to potentially spend billions of dollars on a country that without the support of Russia might face economic collapse.
sent_30: “We should not force our allies to remain dependent on Putin for their energy needs.
sent_31: Ending this de facto ban and expediting approval of natural gas exports is one clear step the U.S. can take to stand by our allies and stand up to Russian aggression, while creating American jobs at the same time.”
sent_32: Some analysts say breaking EU and Ukrainian reliance on Russia’s gas might not only be about the economy, but about something the U.S. has  wanted to do ever since the Cold War : prove it, and not Russia, is the world’s preeminent superpower.
sent_33: “The U.S. has never gotten over the Cold War, and (U.S.) leaders view Russia as a potential adversary,” said Michael Klare, a professor of peace and world security studies at Hampshire College.
sent_34: “ (Russia is) a petro-state.
sent_35: Take that away and Putin’s power disappears.”
sent_4: With tension from military posturing in Crimea increasing, and the potential for bloodshed potent, foreign policy watchers say it’s important to suss out soon why exactly the EU and U.S. — which have been focused inwardly on domestic issues since the global financial crisis — now seem so intent on helping determine the direction of Ukraine.
sent_5: Besides pure altruism, they say the countries have a lot to lose if Ukraine falls further into crisis, and perhaps just as much to gain if it doesn’t.
sent_6: “This is a big country in the center of Europe that can affect the stability of all of Europe,” said William Taylor, vice president at the  U.S. Institute for Peace.
sent_7: “A civil war there would affect energy supplies, trade, everything.”
sent_8: Taylor and others believe all of the West, especially the EU, have a vested economic interested in making sure Ukraine stays stable.
sent_9: For one, the EU exports over $20 billion in goods — primarily machinery, vehicles and industrial chemicals — to  Ukraine annually .
title: What does the West want from Ukraine?

sent_0: VORONEZH — The son of Cuban revolutionary Fidel Castro declared that the island nation recognizes Crimea as a part of Russia and urged the Kremlin to follow Havana's example and stand firm in the face of international sanctions.
sent_1: Fidel Castro Diaz-Balart, scientific adviser of the State Council of the Republic of Cuba and vice president of the Academy of Sciences of Cuba, made the remarks while accepting an honorary doctorate from his former university in Voronezh over the weekend.
sent_10: Castro Diaz-Balart scoffed at the steps that the U.S. and European Union have taken to isolate Russia, including the suspension of its membership in the Group of Eight and the placement of travel bans and asset freezes on people close to Putin.
sent_11: "Cuba has extensive experience of living in isolation from the U.S.," Castro Diaz-Balart said.
sent_12: The Voronezh visit was something of a homecoming for Castro Diaz-Balart, the eldest son of Castro from his first wife.
sent_13: He enrolled at the university as a physical education student in 1968 and changed his major to nuclear physics two years later, acting under the influence of the university's nuclear physicists.
sent_14: He went on to graduate with honors from Moscow State University.
sent_15: Castro Diaz-Balart then worked at the Joint Institute of Nuclear Research in Dubna before earning his first doctorate in 1978.
sent_16: In 1999, he received a second doctorate, this time from the Kurchatov Institute of Nuclear Energy, and he also holds honorary doctorates from Moscow State University and Rostov State University.
sent_17: On Saturday, the Voronezh university gave Diaz-Balart his third honorary doctorate from Russia and an award titled "For Merit to Voronezh State University" at a ceremony attended by Voronezh Governor Alexei Gordeyev.
sent_18: After referring to Crimea and the uprising in Ukraine, Diaz-Balart finished his speech with a quote from his father: "When all great revolutions come to an end, there will only be one left — the great revolution of science and knowledge.
sent_19: And it will never finish."
sent_2: While Russia is under enormous international pressure for annexing Crimea from Ukraine last month, Castro Diaz-Balart reaffirmed that Cuba officially recognized the referendum results in Crimea that paved the way for President Vladimir Putin to sign the annexation agreement.
sent_3: He also noted that Cuba joined 10 other countries in refusing to condemn the annexation during a vote of the United Nations General Assembly on Thursday.
sent_4: One hundred countries approved the resolution, while 58 countries abstained.
sent_5: "During the UN vote, Cuba proved that it remains a friend of Russia and of other countries of the former Soviet Union forever," Castro Diaz-Balart said in the speech Saturday at Voronezh State University.
sent_6: He insisted that Cuba was also a friend of Ukraine.
sent_7: "The people of Ukraine, as I understand it, do not have any claims against the Russians," he said, following the Kremlin line.
sent_8: "It is those in power who are acting in their own self-interest."
sent_9: Fidel Castro Díaz-Balart attending a ceremony where he received an honorary doctorate at Voronezh State University on Saturday.
title: Visiting Russia, Fidel Castro's Son Scoffs at U.S. Sanctions Over Crimea

sent_0: SIMFEROPOL, Ukraine (AFP) - Russian flags flooded Lenin Square in the centre of Crimea's capital Simferopol on Sunday as thousands rallied in support of Moscow's takeover of the peninsula - vastly overwhelming a smaller pro-Ukraine demonstration nearby.
sent_1: The rival rallies in Simferopol were peaceful, in contrast to the Crimean port city of Sevastopol, where about 100 pro-Russians with clubs and whips attacked some 20 people who were guarding a pro-Ukraine rally.
sent_10: "They cannot seize Crimea, (it's an) illegal occupation," he said, as around him unity supporters waved yellow-and-blue balloons marked: "We are for peace in Ukraine".
sent_11: The atmosphere was peaceful, with several dozen police keeping watch on the edges of the crowd.
sent_12: A convoy of about 30 cars tooting their horns and waving Russian flags drove by the rally, prompting shouts of "Shame! Shame!" from participants.
sent_13: Asked why so many more people were at the pro-Russia rally, 32-year-old Mr Anton Vlasenko said they were afraid to stand up to Moscow.
sent_14: "They are scared of the Russian soldiers, they think they have no choice," he said.
sent_15: He said the referendum planned for March 16 on making Crimea part of Russia - announced after pro-Moscow lawmakers seized control and Russian forces flooded into the region - was a farce.
sent_16: "The Kalashnikov is the symbol of Russian democracy," Mr Vlasenko said.
sent_17: Attempts to hold a similar pro-unity demonstration in Sevastopol were met with violence, with the pro-Russian activists attacking some 20 people who were guarding a 200-strong rally in an outer district of the city.
sent_18: The attackers destroyed a car and blocked the vehicles of the security men guarding the crowd, at least five of whom were detained by police.
sent_19: It was unclear whether anybody was seriously injured in the clashes at the rally, which also saw protesters waving the Ukrainian flag and singing the national anthem.
sent_2: Some 10,000 people joined the pro-Russia rally in Simferopol, chanting "Russia! Russia!" as a navy band played patriotic Russian songs and dancers twirled on stage.
sent_3: "We will overcome all adversity, all obstacles and we will restore historic justice," the newly installed pro-Russian Prime Minister of Crimea, Mr Sergei Aksyonov, told the crowd.
sent_4: "Together with Russia we will build our future!" he cried, prompting shouts of "Hurrah! Hurrah!" from the crowd.
sent_5: Standing amidst signs reading "Crimea is not in Ukraine" and "With Russia, Peace in Crimea," 60-year-old Ms Olga said restoring Crimea to Russian rule would undo a historical injustice.
sent_6: "We don't want to be with those Ukrainian fascists any more," said Ms Olga, who declined to give her surname.
sent_7: A few kilometres away, a much smaller crowd of about 1,000 gathered for a more sombre demonstration in support of Crimea remaining within Ukraine.
sent_8: Standing under a bronze bust of Mr Taras Shevchenko - the Ukrainian poet and national hero whose birth 200 years earlier was marked on Sunday - the demonstrators read poetry and sang the national anthem, many with their hands on their hearts.
sent_9: "We are here to honour the great Shevchenko and Ukraine," said Mr Svyatoslav Regushevsky, a 46-year-old who brought his 21/2-year-old son, wearing a ski jacket with the Ukrainian flag colours, to the unity rally.
title: Russian flags flood Crimean capital as thousands back takeover by Russia

sent_0: Seventeen Ukrainian soldiers were killed in clashes with pro-Russian separatists in eastern Ukraine, three days before a presidential election in the former Soviet republic.
sent_1: At least 17 Ukrainian soldiers were killed in clashes with pro-Russian separatists in eastern Ukraine, just three days before a presidential election in the former Soviet republic.
sent_10: Kiev has acknowledged that Sunday's election cannot be held in parts of the Donetsk and Luhansk regions and has accused Moscow of deliberately seeking to undermine Ukrainian democracy, a charge echoed by the United States and European Union.
sent_11: Russia denies the legitimacy of the current Kiev government, which took over after mass street protests toppled Moscow-backed president Viktor Yanukovych in February.
sent_12: He fled to Russia and in March Russia annexed Ukraine's Black Sea peninsula of Crimea.
sent_13: President Vladimir Putin asserts that Moscow has the right to intervene on behalf of Russian speakers outside Russia's borders and has expressed sympathy for people in eastern Ukraine who he says face discrimination and harassment by the Kiev government.
sent_14: Meanwhile a diplomatic row unfolded between Russia and the UK after Prince Charles apparently compared Mr Putin's actions to those of Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler.
sent_15: During a trip to Canada, the 65-year-old prince told a Jewish woman who fled from Poland during World War II that in Ukraine "Putin is doing just about the same as Hitler", according to the Daily Mail newspaper.
sent_16: Charles's remarks, described by a royal source as "well-intentioned" and not meant to be made public, caused a stir in Britain because the royal family is not expected to voice political views in public.
sent_17: "If these words were truly spoken, then, without doubt, they do not reflect well on the future British monarch," a spokesman for the Russian foreign ministry told a news conference.
sent_18: "We view the use of the Western press by members of the British royal family to spread the propaganda campaign against Russia on a pressing issue - that is, the situation in Ukraine - as unacceptable, outrageous and low."
sent_2: Ukraine's health ministry said 16 troops died in a firefight in the town of Volnovakha in the Donetsk region, in addition to one soldier killed in another attack in the neighbouring region of Luhansk.
sent_3: Video posted on YouTube showed men in Ukrainian uniforms taking cover in a field said to be in Volnovakha, as vehicles burned nearby, explosions were heard in the distance, and attack helicopters flew low overhead.
sent_4: The attack happened about 20 kilometres south of the industrial hub of Donetsk, which is now in the hands of separatists who say they will disrupt the election.
sent_5: In Luhansk Ukrainian border guards said they had fought off an attempt by dozens of separatists, armed with grenade launchers and rifles, to enter the region from Russia.
sent_6: The clashes came as Russia moved 15 transport planes and 20 trains carrying personnel and military equipment out of three provinces that border Ukraine, according to the defence ministry.
sent_7: "The moving of units is continuing," Russia's Interfax news agency quoted a defence ministry statement as saying, adding that the troops were returning to their permanent bases after conducting military exercises in the border provinces.
sent_8: NATO chief Anders Fogh Rasmussen said the Russian troop movements "may suggest" preparations for a withdrawal.
sent_9: Ukrainian security forces and the pro-Moscow separatists have clashed repeatedly in recent weeks in eastern Ukraine, where the breakdown of security has rattled the pro-Western interim government in Kiev.
title: Ukraine crisis: Seventeen killed in clashes with pro-Russian separatists near Donetsk

sent_0: Major nationalist role in protests worries many in Ukraine and abroad
sent_1: As Ukraine’s opposition movement vows to continue its “revolution” with more protests and a general strike, an ultra- nationalist party is playing a leading role and former symbols of the far-right fringe are moving into the political mainstream.
sent_10: Today’s “enemies” are president Viktor Yanukovich , whom critics accuse of leading Ukraine away from the European Union and back into Russia’s embrace.
sent_11: Svoboda’s activists are now playing a major role in running Kiev’s main protest camp and buildings occupied by demonstrators.
sent_12: They were also prominent in resisting riot police who tried to storm the camp and in the highly symbolic toppling of a statue of Vladimir Lenin.
sent_13: Svoboda’s leader, former surgeon Oleh Tyahnybok, rouses protesters with firebrand rhetoric attacking the “anti-Ukrainian” forces running the country, and he has met visiting senior EU and US diplomats who would have shunned him in other circumstances.
sent_14: Tyahnybok’s diatribes against corrupt politicians, tycoons and the Kremlin play well with the crowd, and the protests are helping him to push Svoboda towards Ukraine’s political centre.
sent_15: How Svoboda will emerge from Ukraine’s turmoil remains to be seen, but its growing influence, hostility towards Russia and praise for Bandera could deepen the country’s divisions.
sent_16: Svoboda also presents an easy target to the protesters’ foes: Ukraine’s premier Mykola Azarov has called them “Nazis and extremists”, while Russian president Vladimir Putin compared the rallies to a “pogrom”.
sent_2: Flying above crowds in Kiev and other cities, the flags of Ukraine and the European Union mingle with red-and-black “blood and soil” nationalist banners.
sent_3: Across the country, the rallying cry of this revolt booms out countless times every day: “Glory to Ukraine! Glory to the heroes!”
sent_4: The flag and the mantra of the protests were first used by guerrillas in the 1940s, who fought against Nazi and Soviet occupiers in a bid to carve out an independent Ukraine.
sent_5: They are still lionised by many people in western regions, while people in southern and eastern Ukraine, with closer ties to Russia , deride them as Nazi collaborators.
sent_6: Historians say the guerrillas sometimes fought alongside Adolf Hitler’s forces in the hope of securing support for a sovereign Ukraine, and were involved in the killing of tens of thousands of Poles and the German-led mass murder and deportation of Jews.
sent_7: On New Year’s Day, about 15,000 people took part in a torchlit procession through Kiev to mark 105 years since the birth of wartime nationalist leader Stepan Bandera, who is honoured with statues in western Ukraine but reviled in regions closer to Russia, as well as by Jews and Poles.
sent_8: “Glory to the nation, death to the enemies!” chanted the crowd, led by members of a nationalist party called Svoboda (“Freedom”), which has risen rapidly from relative obscurity to be the fourth-largest party in parliament and jointly runs councils in western Ukraine.
sent_9: Liberal opposition parties distanced themselves from the march.
title: Ukraine right revives wartime symbols amid 'revolution'

sent_0: VORONEZH — The son of Cuban revolutionary Fidel Castro declared that the island nation recognizes Crimea as a part of Russia and urged the Kremlin to follow Havana's example and stand firm in the face of international sanctions.
sent_1: Fidel Castro Diaz-Balart, scientific adviser of the State Council of the Republic of Cuba and vice president of the Academy of Sciences of Cuba, made the remarks while accepting an honorary doctorate from his former university in Voronezh over the weekend.
sent_10: Castro Diaz-Balart scoffed at the steps that the U.S. and European Union have taken to isolate Russia, including the suspension of its membership in the Group of Eight and the placement of travel bans and asset freezes on people close to Putin.
sent_11: "Cuba has extensive experience of living in isolation from the U.S.," Castro Diaz-Balart said.
sent_12: The Voronezh visit was something of a homecoming for Castro Diaz-Balart, the eldest son of Castro from his first wife.
sent_13: He enrolled at the university as a physical education student in 1968 and changed his major to nuclear physics two years later, acting under the influence of the university's nuclear physicists.
sent_14: He went on to graduate with honors from Moscow State University.
sent_15: Castro Diaz-Balart then worked at the Joint Institute of Nuclear Research in Dubna before earning his first doctorate in 1978.
sent_16: In 1999, he received a second doctorate, this time from the Kurchatov Institute of Nuclear Energy, and he also holds honorary doctorates from Moscow State University and Rostov State University.
sent_17: On Saturday, the Voronezh university gave Diaz-Balart his third honorary doctorate from Russia and an award titled "For Merit to Voronezh State University" at a ceremony attended by Voronezh Governor Alexei Gordeyev.
sent_18: After referring to Crimea and the uprising in Ukraine, Diaz-Balart finished his speech with a quote from his father: "When all great revolutions come to an end, there will only be one left — the great revolution of science and knowledge.
sent_19: And it will never finish."
sent_2: While Russia is under enormous international pressure for annexing Crimea from Ukraine last month, Castro Diaz-Balart reaffirmed that Cuba officially recognized the referendum results in Crimea that paved the way for President Vladimir Putin to sign the annexation agreement.
sent_3: He also noted that Cuba joined 10 other countries in refusing to condemn the annexation during a vote of the United Nations General Assembly on Thursday.
sent_4: One hundred countries approved the resolution, while 58 countries abstained.
sent_5: "During the UN vote, Cuba proved that it remains a friend of Russia and of other countries of the former Soviet Union forever," Castro Diaz-Balart said in the speech Saturday at Voronezh State University.
sent_6: He insisted that Cuba was also a friend of Ukraine.
sent_7: "The people of Ukraine, as I understand it, do not have any claims against the Russians," he said, following the Kremlin line.
sent_8: "It is those in power who are acting in their own self-interest."

title: Visiting Russia, Fidel Castro's Son Scoffs at U.S. Sanctions Over Crimea

sent_18: And Ukraine has been trying to break away from that dependence for years.
sent_19: In November, it signed a $10 billion deal with Chevron to produce natural gas within Ukraine, but it could also look elsewhere for its supplies.
sent_2: President Barack Obama and leaders from the European Union, for example, have spoken at length on what they want for Ukraine — that it determine its own destiny, and not just any destiny, but one that is different from its past of playing economic lapdog to Russia.
sent_20: As the EU and U.S. discover new ways to extract oil and gas on their own soil — namely through hydraulic fracturing — and build liquefied natural-gas terminals to send it around the world, Ukraine could become a viable market.
sent_21: “The whole natural gas market is changing dramatically,” USIP’s Taylor said.
sent_22: “Over the next five years, there’s going to be dramatic changes in the flows of gas, and the leverage Russians have over the EU and Ukraine is going to decline.”
sent_23: Because Europe also relies heavily on Gazprom, disrupting Ukraine’s relations with Russia is a risky prospect.
sent_24: Some believe it’s no coincidence that the countries that rely most on Russia for gas, especially Germany,  have been more reluctant  than the U.S. to suggest sanctions against Russia.
sent_25: The EU may be seeking a middle ground — making sure the gas can keep flowing while Ukraine also builds closer ties with European countries.
sent_26: At least for the U.S., isolating Gazprom might not be as controversial of an option.
sent_27: In the midst of a hydraulic fracturing-created gas boom, the U.S. has been looking to increase gas exports dramatically over the next few years.
sent_28: So the possibility that Ukraine, and therefore the EU, might break away from Russia’s gas supply might be considered both a geopolitical win and cash bonanza by U.S. politicians.
sent_29: “The United States has abundant supplies of natural gas — an energy source that is in demand by many of our allies — and the U.S. Department of Energy’s excruciatingly slow approval process amounts to a de facto ban on American natural gas exports that Vladimir Putin has happily exploited to finance his geopolitical goals,” House Speaker John Boehner said Tuesday.
sent_3: Going beyond the platitudes of supporting Ukraine's autonomy, however, what has gone without much discussion is why the cash-strapped European Union and the U.S. were motivated to step into the fray — to potentially spend billions of dollars on a country that without the support of Russia might face economic collapse.
sent_30: “We should not force our allies to remain dependent on Putin for their energy needs.
sent_31: Ending this de facto ban and expediting approval of natural gas exports is one clear step the U.S. can take to stand by our allies and stand up to Russian aggression, while creating American jobs at the same time.”
sent_32: Some analysts say breaking EU and Ukrainian reliance on Russia’s gas might not only be about the economy, but about something the U.S. has  wanted to do ever since the Cold War : prove it, and not Russia, is the world’s preeminent superpower.
sent_33: “The U.S. has never gotten over the Cold War, and (U.S.) leaders view Russia as a potential adversary,” said Michael Klare, a professor of peace and world security studies at Hampshire College.
sent_34: “ (Russia is) a petro-state.
sent_35: Take that away and Putin’s power disappears.”

sent_5: Besides pure altruism, they say the countries have a lot to lose if Ukraine falls further into crisis, and perhaps just as much to gain if it doesn’t.
sent_6: “This is a big country in the center of Europe that can affect the stability of all of Europe,” said William Taylor, vice president at the  U.S. Institute for Peace.
sent_7: “A civil war there would affect energy supplies, trade, everything.”

sent_10: The law simply establishes the legal right to implement them," the statement said.

sent_12: Those provisions were removed from the final version of the bill, however.
sent_13: Rights groups had said the law would give the council "draconian" powers to restrict media and could return a nation once celebrated for media freedoms to Soviet-era levels of censorship.

sent_17: The measure says Ukraine will hold 51 percent and foreign partners will be offered 49 percent in the venture.
sent_18: It covers both transit pipelines and underground gas-storage facilities.
sent_19: The law passed by 228 votes -- two more than the minimum necessary.

sent_0: Public opinion poll was conducted by the Ilko  Kucheriv Democratic Initiatives Foundation together with Kyiv International Institute of Sociology  in the period between February, 8-18 2014.
sent_1: 2032 respondents were interviewed  in all the districts  of Ukraine (including  Kyiv) and in Crimea according to the random sample, which was representative for  all the population of Ukraine older than 18 years.
sent_10: The main part of  supporters of this idea of unification with Russia is in the East (26%) and South (19%), while the smallest part is in the Center (5%) and West (1%) of Ukraine.
sent_11: By regions  majority of integration with Russia in one state  is in Crimea  (41%), Donetsk district (33%), Lugansk district (24%), Odessa district (24%), Zaporizhzhya (17%) and Kharkiv  (15%) districts, but even there  support  to the current status of relations  with Russia   - as two independent and  friendly  states – prevails.
sent_12: Among Russians  desire to have Ukraine and Russia as two independent and friendly states (with open borders, without visas and customs houses) prevails as well as among Ukrainians (68% and 63% respectively).
sent_13: Integration into one state is supported  by 9% of Ukrainians and 32% of Russians.
sent_14: There is direct dependence  between  desire to unite with Russia into  a single state and age of respondents:  among youth   up to 30 years old  5% want this unification to be realized, among people of 30-54 years old – 11% support that, and  among people older than 55 years – 17%.
sent_15: It is obvious, that among supporters of joining the Custom Union, there is more people supporting unification  with Russia  (26,5%), than among  those, oriented on joining the EU (1%).
sent_16: However,  even among supporters of entering the Custom Union  majority   wants  to preserve the status-quo in relations with Russia (69%).
sent_17: Among  people, having negative attitude towards Maidan,  only 21% wants to unite with Russia into a single state.
sent_18: Among supporters of political parties  the highest percentage  of people, who wants join Ukraine to join Russia, is among  communists’ electorate  (35,5%), but even in this case majority  consider that Ukraine and Russia should be friendly independent states (63%).
sent_19: Among  Party of Regions  voters 28% support unification with Russia.
sent_2: Statistical error doesn’t  exceed  2,2% (without design -effect).
sent_20: In Russia  16% of population support  unification with Ukraine into one state.
sent_3: Question included by  the Ilko Kucheriv Democratic Initiatives Foundation were financed  in the framework of the project “Public sociological consortium” by the European union, MATRA programme  of the Kingdom of Netherlands, International Renaissance Foundation, and also  in the framework of the project  “Stimulating dialog on transition processes” by the National Endowment for Democracy (USA).
sent_4: Data from public opinion poll, conducted by Russian research organization Levada Centre  is provided for comparison.
sent_5: Levada Centre  conducted  representative for Russia public opinion poll  on February,  21-25 2014 and interviewed  1603 respondents older than 18 years in 130 settlements in 45 districts of the country.
sent_6: Statistical error doesn’t exceed 3,4%.
sent_7: Ukrainians don’t want visas and borders with Russia, but at the same time don’t want  to be united with Russia  in a single state   In Ukraine, as well as in Russia  majority of respondents  wants both countries to be independent, but friendly  - with open borders, without visas and customs houses (in Ukraine – 68%, in Russia – 59%).
sent_8: In Ukraine  with numbers  have decreased  since November, 2013 by 5%, in Russia – increased  by 4%.
sent_9: Integration with  Russia into a single state   is supported by 12% of respondents in Ukraine, and  during recent years  this number has decreased from 20% to 9%,  but after Maidan – increased by 3%.
title: HOW RELATIONS BETWEEN UKRAINE AND RUSSIA SHOULD LOOK LIKE? PUBLIC OPINION POLL RESULTS

sent_0: The Ukraine government reportedly sent protesters in Kiev a creepy text message.
sent_1: This is how they could have done it.
sent_10: There are a few different ways the Ukrainian government could have done it, according to Ashkan Soltani, an independent privacy researcher.
sent_11: The easiest would have been for the government to ask Ukrainian cellphone providers to give them a list of numbers that were connected to a certain cellphone tower, or a few towers, in a certain interval of time.
sent_12: This is what is commonly referred to as " tower dumps ."
sent_13: This would imply the collaboration of the cellphone companies, but all the major Ukrainian providers on Tuesday denied they had anything to do with this incident.
sent_14: "We declare our innocence," wrote MTS on its Facebook page according to a translation of the statement.
sent_15: "It was carried out by using equipment that does not belong to MTS."
sent_16: Another provider, Kyivstar, penned a similar denial.
sent_17: "Attackers are using illegal equipment for such mailings.
sent_18: We know of the existence of equipment (the so-called 'pirate base stations') that allows you to send SMS and make calls to mobile phones subscribers to any operators that are in a certain area," the company wrote on Facebook.
sent_19: Here's the catch: The equipment to which they refer actually exists, and with it authorities wouldn't need the providers' help to identify whoever was in downtown Kiev near the protests and send them the text messages.
sent_2: As mass riots continued on the streets of Kiev, protesters, as well as other people in the area, received a mysterious text message on Monday evening.
sent_20: The easiest way would be to use a so-called "IMSI catcher," which is a portable device built to act as a cell tower and trick nearby cellphones into connecting to it, Soltani explained to Mashable .
sent_21: "They're essentially fake base stations," Soltani told Mashable .
sent_22: Once a cellphone is connected to one of these International Mobile Subscriber Number (IMSI) catchers, the device captures a deluge of information, including identifying details such as the IMSI and the Electronic Serial Number (ESM).
sent_23: Once the IMSI catcher is connected to a series of cellphones, it can broadcast text messages like the one the protesters received.
sent_24: Devices like these are normally employed by police departments to track suspected criminals, but their use has stirred controversy because they don't discriminate.
sent_25: Any cellphone in their range gets caught in their surveillance net, and these devices are also designed to intercept phone calls and messages.
sent_26: There are a lot of commercial IMSI catchers , costing anywhere from $20,000 to around $140,000, depending on their features and range.
sent_27: They are sometimes referred to as "Stingrays," from the most widely known of this devices, made by Harris Corporation .
sent_28: But hackers have been able to build similar machines with just $1,500.
sent_29: According to Costin Raiu, a security researcher at Kaspersky Lab, this is the most likely theory, assuming the cellphone providers did not cooperate.
sent_3: "Dear subscriber, you are registered as a participant in a mass disturbance," the message read, as first reported by The New York Times .
sent_30: While it's still unclear who sent these messages in Kiev, it's clear why they did it.
sent_31: "You can scare people into thinking that they have been targeted much more narrowly by writing a message that implies essentially 'we caught you personally rioting,'" said Galperin.
sent_32: The protesters, however, were not scared away, as clashes continued after the message was broadcast.
sent_4: The text came from a number only identified as 111, but the Times suggests Ukrainian authorities were behind it.
sent_5: The country's Interior Ministry, however, denied sending the messages, as later reported by The Guardian .
sent_6: But regardless of who was responsible for the SMS messages, how did they do it?
sent_7: How did they pinpoint only certain cellphones in a specific area?
sent_8: It turns out, something like this wouldn't be that hard to carry out.
sent_9: "It is very easy to send messages out to everybody who was in one particular area, at one particular time," said Eva Galperin, an activist at the Electronic Frontier Foundation and an expert in surveillance technology.
title: Someone Sent a Mysterious Mass Text to Protesters in Kiev

sent_0: The Ukraine government reportedly sent protesters in Kiev a creepy text message.
sent_1: This is how they could have done it.

sent_11: The easiest would have been for the government to ask Ukrainian cellphone providers to give them a list of numbers that were connected to a certain cellphone tower, or a few towers, in a certain interval of time.
sent_12: This is what is commonly referred to as " tower dumps ."
sent_13: This would imply the collaboration of the cellphone companies, but all the major Ukrainian providers on Tuesday denied they had anything to do with this incident.
sent_14: "We declare our innocence," wrote MTS on its Facebook page according to a translation of the statement.
sent_15: "It was carried out by using equipment that does not belong to MTS."
sent_16: Another provider, Kyivstar, penned a similar denial.
sent_17: "Attackers are using illegal equipment for such mailings.
sent_18: We know of the existence of equipment (the so-called 'pirate base stations') that allows you to send SMS and make calls to mobile phones subscribers to any operators that are in a certain area," the company wrote on Facebook.
sent_19: Here's the catch: The equipment to which they refer actually exists, and with it authorities wouldn't need the providers' help to identify whoever was in downtown Kiev near the protests and send them the text messages.
sent_2: As mass riots continued on the streets of Kiev, protesters, as well as other people in the area, received a mysterious text message on Monday evening.
sent_20: The easiest way would be to use a so-called "IMSI catcher," which is a portable device built to act as a cell tower and trick nearby cellphones into connecting to it, Soltani explained to Mashable .
sent_21: "They're essentially fake base stations," Soltani told Mashable .
sent_22: Once a cellphone is connected to one of these International Mobile Subscriber Number (IMSI) catchers, the device captures a deluge of information, including identifying details such as the IMSI and the Electronic Serial Number (ESM).
sent_23: Once the IMSI catcher is connected to a series of cellphones, it can broadcast text messages like the one the protesters received.
sent_24: Devices like these are normally employed by police departments to track suspected criminals, but their use has stirred controversy because they don't discriminate.
sent_25: Any cellphone in their range gets caught in their surveillance net, and these devices are also designed to intercept phone calls and messages.
sent_26: There are a lot of commercial IMSI catchers , costing anywhere from $20,000 to around $140,000, depending on their features and range.
sent_27: They are sometimes referred to as "Stingrays," from the most widely known of this devices, made by Harris Corporation .
sent_28: But hackers have been able to build similar machines with just $1,500.
sent_29: According to Costin Raiu, a security researcher at Kaspersky Lab, this is the most likely theory, assuming the cellphone providers did not cooperate.
sent_3: "Dear subscriber, you are registered as a participant in a mass disturbance," the message read, as first reported by The New York Times .
sent_30: While it's still unclear who sent these messages in Kiev, it's clear why they did it.
sent_31: "You can scare people into thinking that they have been targeted much more narrowly by writing a message that implies essentially 'we caught you personally rioting,'" said Galperin.
sent_32: The protesters, however, were not scared away, as clashes continued after the message was broadcast.
sent_4: The text came from a number only identified as 111, but the Times suggests Ukrainian authorities were behind it.
sent_5: The country's Interior Ministry, however, denied sending the messages, as later reported by The Guardian .
sent_6: But regardless of who was responsible for the SMS messages, how did they do it?
sent_7: How did they pinpoint only certain cellphones in a specific area?
sent_8: It turns out, something like this wouldn't be that hard to carry out.
sent_9: "It is very easy to send messages out to everybody who was in one particular area, at one particular time," said Eva Galperin, an activist at the Electronic Frontier Foundation and an expert in surveillance technology.
title: Someone Sent a Mysterious Mass Text to Protesters in Kiev

sent_0: Ukraine's parliament has passed legislation that would allow the government to impose sanctions on Russia.
sent_1: The bill was approved in a final reading on August 14.
sent_10: The law simply establishes the legal right to implement them," the statement said.
sent_11: A version of the bill passed on first reading on August 12 had included provisions allowing the censoring of media deemed a national security threat.
sent_12: Those provisions were removed from the final version of the bill, however.
sent_13: Rights groups had said the law would give the council "draconian" powers to restrict media and could return a nation once celebrated for media freedoms to Soviet-era levels of censorship.
sent_14: In a statement, the representative on media freedom for the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), Dunja Mijatovic, welcomed the move to drop the media provisions as a "step in the right direction."
sent_15: "The provisions could potentially endanger free media and pluralism in Ukraine," she said, "and by dropping them the legislators have taken a decision to protect and ensure free media and freedom of expression, rather than restricting free speech."
sent_16: Also on August 14, Ukraine's parliament approved a bill to allow gas-transit facilities to be leased on a joint-venture basis with participation from EU and U.S. firms.
sent_17: The measure says Ukraine will hold 51 percent and foreign partners will be offered 49 percent in the venture.
sent_18: It covers both transit pipelines and underground gas-storage facilities.
sent_19: The law passed by 228 votes -- two more than the minimum necessary.
sent_2: It provides for sanctions against 172 individuals and 65 entities in Russia and other countries for supporting and financing "terrorism" in Ukraine, though actual sanctions would need approval from Ukraine's National Security and Defense Council.
sent_20: Ukraine is making efforts to become less dependent on Russian gas after suffering three cutoffs of natural-gas supplies from Russia in less than nine years.
sent_21: At the same time, Kyiv wants to provide more reliable transit for Russian gas to the EU market.
sent_22: Kyiv says the measure will bring in investment and remove the need for the South Stream pipeline, which Russia is building to take gas to southeastern Europe across the Black Sea, bypassing Ukraine.
sent_3: A total of 244 lawmakers in the Verkhovna Rada supported the sanctions.
sent_4: Prime Minister Arseniy Yatsenyuk told parliament after the August 14 vote that Ukraine had taken a historic step.
sent_5: "By approving the law on sanctions, we showed that the country is able to protect itself," he said.
sent_6: "The law should give a clear answer to any aggressor or terrorist who threatens our national security, our government, and our citizens."
sent_7: The names of those Russian individuals and companies targeted by the sanctions will not be published until President Petro Poroshenko has signed the law into force.
sent_8: Naftohaz, Ukraine's state-run energy firm, said in a statement on August 13 that future sanctions against Russia would not necessarily target Russia's gas giant Gazprom, however.
sent_9: "The adoption of the sanctions law will not lead automatically to sanctions against any entity, including Gazprom.
title: Ukraine Passes Law On Russia Sanctions, Gas Pipelines
