sent_0: Nickolay Mladenov: All agreed that a political solution to the problem in Afghanistan should be found, Deutsche Welle Radio, January 29, 2010  ...
sent_1: Host: In connection with the London Conference on Afghanistan, our London correspondent Andrei Vladov talked about the Bulgarian commitments at Hindukush with Nickolay Mladenov, the Bulgarian Minister of Foreign  Affairs and until quite recently  Minister of Defence, who is participating in the conference.
sent_10: In addition, Bulgaria will join the European Union Police Mission to help with the training of the Afghan police as part of the NATO security mission.
sent_11: A.Vladov: And yet isn’t civilian presence lagging behind Bulgaria’s military presence?
sent_12: I am drawing a parallel with the situation in Iraq and the deep disappointment of the Bulgarian public that Bulgarian companies failed to win lucrative contracts for the  reconstruction of the country.
sent_13: Do you think that Bulgaria has learned from this experience and can something be done to ensure that Bulgarian companies will participate in the construction of infrastructure in Afghanistan?
sent_14: N.Mladenov: You are absolutely right about Iraq.
sent_15: However, there is no comparing Iraq with Afghanistan at this point.
sent_16: It will take quite some time for the situation in Afghanistan to make possible some form of more direct economic participation.
sent_17: An interesting initiative was suggested today - that an economic forum be organised in Turkey for the entire region around Afghanistan to seek out such opportunities.
sent_18: However, it is still early days for this.
sent_19: Today’s main conclusion is that all agreed that yes, a political solution should be found to the problem in Afghanistan, but there must be some form of peace first.
sent_2: Nickolay Mladenov: Bulgaria is participating quite strongly in the international operation in Afghanistan.
sent_20: Host: This was Andrei Vladov talking with the Bulgarian Minister of Foreign  Affairs, Nickolay Mladenov.
sent_3: Our contingent at the moment is nearly 500-strong, with troops in Kabul and Kandahar and medical teams in Kabul and Herat.
sent_4: The government decided a while ago, early this year, to boost the size of our contingent in Kandahar with 30 people.
sent_5: This is something I reaffirmed in London, and a further 70 or so people will be sent by the year’s end because the international operation for stabilisation of Afghanistan requires that in addition to the United States boosting troop numbers by 30,000, the other countries should also contribute according to their capabilities.
sent_6: We saw, for example, that Romania doubled its military contingent in Afghanistan from 800 to 1,600.
sent_7: And Germany doubled its financial assistance.
sent_8: Andrei Vladov: Does that mean that at least for now Bulgaria is not considering phasing out of Afghanistan? N.Mladenov: The government has a mandate from the National Assembly until the completion of the international mission for stabilisation of Afghanistan.
sent_9: Therefore all our efforts are concentrated within this mandate.
title: Statement of the MFA of the Republic of Bulgaria on the escalation of the situation in Ukraine

sent_0: Legal amendments introduced Thursday that classify as state secrets any losses sustained during peacetime special operations are further confirmation of Russia's direct involvement in the Ukraine conflict, legal and military experts told The Moscow Times.
sent_1: The amendments, signed by President Vladimir Putin, make "information disclosing the loss of personnel … during special operations in peacetime" a classified state secret.
sent_10: Truth and Consequences
sent_11: Since the conflict in eastern Ukraine broke out following a popular uprising that toppled the former pro-Russian president Viktor Yanukovych last year, many journalists have investigated reports of Russian troops fighting — and dying — there.
sent_12: The Kremlin denies there are Russian soldiers fighting on the side of pro-Russian rebels in Ukraine.
sent_13: Last August the Pskovskaya Guberniya newspaper published a series of articles alleging that secret funerals had been held for paratroopers from a local regiment believed to have been killed fighting in Ukraine.
sent_14: One of the newspaper's main writers, Lev Shlosberg, was severely beaten by three unidentified men shortly afterwards.
sent_15: Leading Russian opposition politician Boris Nemtsov was also working on a report about alleged Russian troop losses in Ukraine at the time of his murder in central Moscow in February.
sent_16: Other journalists and human rights groups have attempted to find proof that the Russian army is directly involved in helping pro-Russian insurgents in Ukraine.
sent_17: The St. Petersburg branch of the Soldiers' Mothers Committee — an organization that campaigns to defend the rights of soldiers and their families — sent around 30 requests for information to military units that soldiers' families and media reports have identified as suffering losses in 2014.
sent_18: Only one unit responded in full, according to the NGO's spokesman Alexander Peredruk.
sent_19: "The main consequence of this law is that it will basically be impossible to obtain information," Peredruk said in a phone interview with The Moscow Times.
sent_2: Putin has repeatedly denied any involvement of Russian troops in the armed conflict in eastern Ukraine.
sent_20: "We won't know what the statistics are, but the truth is, we didn't know before either," he said.
sent_21: After Russia's five-day war with Georgia in South Ossetia, which was referred to as a special operation, the General Staff announced that it had lost 74 servicemen there.
sent_22: According to Alexander Khramchikhin, deputy director of the Institute for Political and Military Analysis think tank, there is no internationally accepted norm for classifying special military operations.
sent_23: "Each country handles these questions its own way; for many this is not an issue.
sent_24: In the United States, such operations are completely classified," he told The Moscow Times in a phone interview.
sent_25: Ordinary Victims
sent_26: The key point of the legal amendments is that ordinary people will suffer as a result of them, said Grigory Pasko, a military journalist and director of the Moscow-based Foundation for Investigative Journalism.
sent_27: "The main victims of this decree are parents and relatives and also soldiers themselves who have gone missing or were killed in combat," he said.
sent_28: A former officer of the Russian Navy, Pasko served a prison term for espionage in connection with research he did for a report on environmental issues in the Sea of Japan.
sent_29: Pasko said the Russian state already has all the necessary means to protect its secrets.
sent_3: Asked to explain Putin's move Thursday, his spokesman Dmitry Peskov had no immediate comment, Reuters reported.
sent_30: The high treason article of the Russian Criminal Code says that in addition to espionage and disclosure of state secrets, "any other assistance rendered to a foreign state, a foreign organization or their representatives in hostile activities to the detriment of the external security of the Russian Federation" shall be punishable by up to 20 years in prison.
sent_31: Svetlana Davydova, a mother of seven, was detained in January on suspicion of high treason over a phone call she made to the Ukrainian Embassy in which she warned that Russian troops might have been deployed to eastern Ukraine.
sent_32: She was released and the charges dropped in February.
sent_4: Military servicemen who are killed, injured or go missing can be considered military losses, meaning their relatives will be forced to keep information about their deaths a secret, lawyers said Thursday.
sent_5: "Even a death notification sent to parents or other relatives [of a soldier] can be considered a secret under this decree," Ivan Pavlov, a leading lawyer in the field of government transparency who has successfully defended treason suspects, told The Moscow Times.
sent_6: The federal list of what constitutes a state secret can be accessed publicly, but government agencies also compile their own lists that are themselves usually classified.
sent_7: Moreover, what the Defense Ministry classifies as a secret could be considered open information by the Interior Ministry, Pavlov said.
sent_8: "If a citizen, for instance a journalist, obtains information that is considered a state secret, they face prison.
sent_9: The problem is that they might not even know it was a state secret," said Pavlov, who successfully defended Alexander Nikitin, a former nuclear inspector who was accused in the 1990s of espionage for raising the alarm about the dangers posed by decaying nuclear submarines.
title: Putin Classifying Troop Losses Proves They're in Ukraine – Analysts

sent_15: Many were sceptical about the eventual success of demonstrators.
sent_16: Fico was mum on the events in Ukraine until December 3 of last year, when he said that the EU is “so in love with itself” that it is convinced there is no better alternative to it in the world, SITA reported.

sent_19: But as demonstrations have persisted and confrontations have increased in frequency and intensity, such comments are increasingly seen as out of step with the European mainstream.

sent_22: “If the European Union is true to its values, then obviously we cannot remain silent in this gross violation of not only democratic principles, but of the law.”
sent_3: We have very actively been supporting a European way for Ukraine.”
sent_4: The United States has imposed visa restrictions on Ukrainian officials connected to the violence in the wake of allegations that two protesters were shot and killed by security forces.

sent_6: “There is a saying that if a leader does not want to listen to his people, he will hear from them,” Lajčák said.
sent_7: “That is exactly what is happening in Ukraine.”

sent_9: He condemned the intervention of specialised security units in Kiev resulting in the death of several demonstrators as unacceptable, noting that Ukraine is Slovakia’s neighbour “with which we have many things in common”.

sent_0: Legal amendments introduced Thursday that classify as state secrets any losses sustained during peacetime special operations are further confirmation of Russia's direct involvement in the Ukraine conflict, legal and military experts told The Moscow Times.
sent_1: The amendments, signed by President Vladimir Putin, make "information disclosing the loss of personnel … during special operations in peacetime" a classified state secret.
sent_10: Truth and Consequences
sent_11: Since the conflict in eastern Ukraine broke out following a popular uprising that toppled the former pro-Russian president Viktor Yanukovych last year, many journalists have investigated reports of Russian troops fighting — and dying — there.
sent_12: The Kremlin denies there are Russian soldiers fighting on the side of pro-Russian rebels in Ukraine.
sent_13: Last August the Pskovskaya Guberniya newspaper published a series of articles alleging that secret funerals had been held for paratroopers from a local regiment believed to have been killed fighting in Ukraine.
sent_14: One of the newspaper's main writers, Lev Shlosberg, was severely beaten by three unidentified men shortly afterwards.
sent_15: Leading Russian opposition politician Boris Nemtsov was also working on a report about alleged Russian troop losses in Ukraine at the time of his murder in central Moscow in February.
sent_16: Other journalists and human rights groups have attempted to find proof that the Russian army is directly involved in helping pro-Russian insurgents in Ukraine.
sent_17: The St. Petersburg branch of the Soldiers' Mothers Committee — an organization that campaigns to defend the rights of soldiers and their families — sent around 30 requests for information to military units that soldiers' families and media reports have identified as suffering losses in 2014.
sent_18: Only one unit responded in full, according to the NGO's spokesman Alexander Peredruk.
sent_19: "The main consequence of this law is that it will basically be impossible to obtain information," Peredruk said in a phone interview with The Moscow Times.
sent_2: Putin has repeatedly denied any involvement of Russian troops in the armed conflict in eastern Ukraine.
sent_20: "We won't know what the statistics are, but the truth is, we didn't know before either," he said.
sent_21: After Russia's five-day war with Georgia in South Ossetia, which was referred to as a special operation, the General Staff announced that it had lost 74 servicemen there.
sent_22: According to Alexander Khramchikhin, deputy director of the Institute for Political and Military Analysis think tank, there is no internationally accepted norm for classifying special military operations.
sent_23: "Each country handles these questions its own way; for many this is not an issue.
sent_24: In the United States, such operations are completely classified," he told The Moscow Times in a phone interview.
sent_25: Ordinary Victims
sent_26: The key point of the legal amendments is that ordinary people will suffer as a result of them, said Grigory Pasko, a military journalist and director of the Moscow-based Foundation for Investigative Journalism.
sent_27: "The main victims of this decree are parents and relatives and also soldiers themselves who have gone missing or were killed in combat," he said.
sent_28: A former officer of the Russian Navy, Pasko served a prison term for espionage in connection with research he did for a report on environmental issues in the Sea of Japan.
sent_29: Pasko said the Russian state already has all the necessary means to protect its secrets.
sent_3: Asked to explain Putin's move Thursday, his spokesman Dmitry Peskov had no immediate comment, Reuters reported.
sent_30: The high treason article of the Russian Criminal Code says that in addition to espionage and disclosure of state secrets, "any other assistance rendered to a foreign state, a foreign organization or their representatives in hostile activities to the detriment of the external security of the Russian Federation" shall be punishable by up to 20 years in prison.
sent_31: Svetlana Davydova, a mother of seven, was detained in January on suspicion of high treason over a phone call she made to the Ukrainian Embassy in which she warned that Russian troops might have been deployed to eastern Ukraine.
sent_32: She was released and the charges dropped in February.
sent_4: Military servicemen who are killed, injured or go missing can be considered military losses, meaning their relatives will be forced to keep information about their deaths a secret, lawyers said Thursday.
sent_5: "Even a death notification sent to parents or other relatives [of a soldier] can be considered a secret under this decree," Ivan Pavlov, a leading lawyer in the field of government transparency who has successfully defended treason suspects, told The Moscow Times.
sent_6: The federal list of what constitutes a state secret can be accessed publicly, but government agencies also compile their own lists that are themselves usually classified.
sent_7: Moreover, what the Defense Ministry classifies as a secret could be considered open information by the Interior Ministry, Pavlov said.
sent_8: "If a citizen, for instance a journalist, obtains information that is considered a state secret, they face prison.
sent_9: The problem is that they might not even know it was a state secret," said Pavlov, who successfully defended Alexander Nikitin, a former nuclear inspector who was accused in the 1990s of espionage for raising the alarm about the dangers posed by decaying nuclear submarines.
title: Putin Classifying Troop Losses Proves They're in Ukraine – Analysts

sent_0: Major nationalist role in protests worries many in Ukraine and abroad
sent_1: As Ukraine’s opposition movement vows to continue its “revolution” with more protests and a general strike, an ultra- nationalist party is playing a leading role and former symbols of the far-right fringe are moving into the political mainstream.
sent_10: Today’s “enemies” are president Viktor Yanukovich , whom critics accuse of leading Ukraine away from the European Union and back into Russia’s embrace.
sent_11: Svoboda’s activists are now playing a major role in running Kiev’s main protest camp and buildings occupied by demonstrators.
sent_12: They were also prominent in resisting riot police who tried to storm the camp and in the highly symbolic toppling of a statue of Vladimir Lenin.
sent_13: Svoboda’s leader, former surgeon Oleh Tyahnybok, rouses protesters with firebrand rhetoric attacking the “anti-Ukrainian” forces running the country, and he has met visiting senior EU and US diplomats who would have shunned him in other circumstances.
sent_14: Tyahnybok’s diatribes against corrupt politicians, tycoons and the Kremlin play well with the crowd, and the protests are helping him to push Svoboda towards Ukraine’s political centre.
sent_15: How Svoboda will emerge from Ukraine’s turmoil remains to be seen, but its growing influence, hostility towards Russia and praise for Bandera could deepen the country’s divisions.
sent_16: Svoboda also presents an easy target to the protesters’ foes: Ukraine’s premier Mykola Azarov has called them “Nazis and extremists”, while Russian president Vladimir Putin compared the rallies to a “pogrom”.
sent_2: Flying above crowds in Kiev and other cities, the flags of Ukraine and the European Union mingle with red-and-black “blood and soil” nationalist banners.
sent_3: Across the country, the rallying cry of this revolt booms out countless times every day: “Glory to Ukraine! Glory to the heroes!”
sent_4: The flag and the mantra of the protests were first used by guerrillas in the 1940s, who fought against Nazi and Soviet occupiers in a bid to carve out an independent Ukraine.
sent_5: They are still lionised by many people in western regions, while people in southern and eastern Ukraine, with closer ties to Russia , deride them as Nazi collaborators.
sent_6: Historians say the guerrillas sometimes fought alongside Adolf Hitler’s forces in the hope of securing support for a sovereign Ukraine, and were involved in the killing of tens of thousands of Poles and the German-led mass murder and deportation of Jews.
sent_7: On New Year’s Day, about 15,000 people took part in a torchlit procession through Kiev to mark 105 years since the birth of wartime nationalist leader Stepan Bandera, who is honoured with statues in western Ukraine but reviled in regions closer to Russia, as well as by Jews and Poles.
sent_8: “Glory to the nation, death to the enemies!” chanted the crowd, led by members of a nationalist party called Svoboda (“Freedom”), which has risen rapidly from relative obscurity to be the fourth-largest party in parliament and jointly runs councils in western Ukraine.
sent_9: Liberal opposition parties distanced themselves from the march.
title: Ukraine right revives wartime symbols amid 'revolution'

sent_0: Seventeen Ukrainian soldiers were killed in clashes with pro-Russian separatists in eastern Ukraine, three days before a presidential election in the former Soviet republic.

title: Ukraine crisis: Seventeen killed in clashes with pro-Russian separatists near Donetsk

sent_19: It was unclear whether anybody was seriously injured in the clashes at the rally, which also saw protesters waving the Ukrainian flag and singing the national anthem.

title: Russian flags flood Crimean capital as thousands back takeover by Russia

title: Third Wave of Sanctions Slams Russian Stocks

title: US Imposes Sanctions on 7 Russians, 17 Russian Companies

sent_0: On May 1.the Polish Air Force will take responsibility for the Baltic Air Policing: four MiG-29 Fulcrums accompanied by more than 100 soldiers will deploy to Lithuania.

sent_10: KC-135Rs operating from Germany provide the air-refueling support.

sent_0: Legal amendments introduced Thursday that classify as state secrets any losses sustained during peacetime special operations are further confirmation of Russia's direct involvement in the Ukraine conflict, legal and military experts told The Moscow Times.
sent_1: The amendments, signed by President Vladimir Putin, make "information disclosing the loss of personnel … during special operations in peacetime" a classified state secret.
sent_10: Truth and Consequences
sent_11: Since the conflict in eastern Ukraine broke out following a popular uprising that toppled the former pro-Russian president Viktor Yanukovych last year, many journalists have investigated reports of Russian troops fighting — and dying — there.
sent_12: The Kremlin denies there are Russian soldiers fighting on the side of pro-Russian rebels in Ukraine.
sent_13: Last August the Pskovskaya Guberniya newspaper published a series of articles alleging that secret funerals had been held for paratroopers from a local regiment believed to have been killed fighting in Ukraine.
sent_14: One of the newspaper's main writers, Lev Shlosberg, was severely beaten by three unidentified men shortly afterwards.
sent_15: Leading Russian opposition politician Boris Nemtsov was also working on a report about alleged Russian troop losses in Ukraine at the time of his murder in central Moscow in February.
sent_16: Other journalists and human rights groups have attempted to find proof that the Russian army is directly involved in helping pro-Russian insurgents in Ukraine.
sent_17: The St. Petersburg branch of the Soldiers' Mothers Committee — an organization that campaigns to defend the rights of soldiers and their families — sent around 30 requests for information to military units that soldiers' families and media reports have identified as suffering losses in 2014.
sent_18: Only one unit responded in full, according to the NGO's spokesman Alexander Peredruk.
sent_19: "The main consequence of this law is that it will basically be impossible to obtain information," Peredruk said in a phone interview with The Moscow Times.
sent_2: Putin has repeatedly denied any involvement of Russian troops in the armed conflict in eastern Ukraine.
sent_20: "We won't know what the statistics are, but the truth is, we didn't know before either," he said.
sent_21: After Russia's five-day war with Georgia in South Ossetia, which was referred to as a special operation, the General Staff announced that it had lost 74 servicemen there.
sent_22: According to Alexander Khramchikhin, deputy director of the Institute for Political and Military Analysis think tank, there is no internationally accepted norm for classifying special military operations.
sent_23: "Each country handles these questions its own way; for many this is not an issue.
sent_24: In the United States, such operations are completely classified," he told The Moscow Times in a phone interview.
sent_25: Ordinary Victims
sent_26: The key point of the legal amendments is that ordinary people will suffer as a result of them, said Grigory Pasko, a military journalist and director of the Moscow-based Foundation for Investigative Journalism.
sent_27: "The main victims of this decree are parents and relatives and also soldiers themselves who have gone missing or were killed in combat," he said.
sent_28: A former officer of the Russian Navy, Pasko served a prison term for espionage in connection with research he did for a report on environmental issues in the Sea of Japan.
sent_29: Pasko said the Russian state already has all the necessary means to protect its secrets.
sent_3: Asked to explain Putin's move Thursday, his spokesman Dmitry Peskov had no immediate comment, Reuters reported.
sent_30: The high treason article of the Russian Criminal Code says that in addition to espionage and disclosure of state secrets, "any other assistance rendered to a foreign state, a foreign organization or their representatives in hostile activities to the detriment of the external security of the Russian Federation" shall be punishable by up to 20 years in prison.
sent_31: Svetlana Davydova, a mother of seven, was detained in January on suspicion of high treason over a phone call she made to the Ukrainian Embassy in which she warned that Russian troops might have been deployed to eastern Ukraine.
sent_32: She was released and the charges dropped in February.
sent_4: Military servicemen who are killed, injured or go missing can be considered military losses, meaning their relatives will be forced to keep information about their deaths a secret, lawyers said Thursday.
sent_5: "Even a death notification sent to parents or other relatives [of a soldier] can be considered a secret under this decree," Ivan Pavlov, a leading lawyer in the field of government transparency who has successfully defended treason suspects, told The Moscow Times.
sent_6: The federal list of what constitutes a state secret can be accessed publicly, but government agencies also compile their own lists that are themselves usually classified.
sent_7: Moreover, what the Defense Ministry classifies as a secret could be considered open information by the Interior Ministry, Pavlov said.
sent_8: "If a citizen, for instance a journalist, obtains information that is considered a state secret, they face prison.
sent_9: The problem is that they might not even know it was a state secret," said Pavlov, who successfully defended Alexander Nikitin, a former nuclear inspector who was accused in the 1990s of espionage for raising the alarm about the dangers posed by decaying nuclear submarines.
